# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: transfer-learning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:transfer-learning/few-shot-learning] The limiting case of few-shot learning is zero-shot learning that requires no training on examples of the class to be classified; instead, the classification task must be generalized from examples of other classes.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] In deep learning, **fine-tuning** is the process of adapting a computational model trained for one task (the *upstream task*) to perform a different, usually more specific, task (the *downstream task*).
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] It is considered a form of transfer learning, as it reuses knowledge learned from the original training objective.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning involves applying additional training (e.g., on new data) to the parameters of a neural network that have been pre-trained.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] The additional training can be applied to the entire neural network, or to only a subset of its layers, in which case the layers that are not being fine-tuned are "frozen" (i.e., not changed during backpropagation).
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] A model may also be augmented with "adapters"—lightweight modules inserted into the model's architecture that nudge the embedding space for domain adaptation.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] These contain far fewer parameters than the original model and can be fine-tuned in a parameter-efficient way by tuning only their weights and leaving the rest of the model's weights frozen.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Models that are pre-trained on large, general corpora are usually fine-tuned by reusing their parameters as a starting point and adding a task-specific layer trained from scratch.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning the full model is also common and often yields better results, but is more computationally expensive.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning is typically accomplished via supervised learning, but there are also techniques to fine-tune a model using weak supervision.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning can be combined with a reinforcement learning from human feedback-based objective to produce language models such as ChatGPT (a fine-tuned version of GPT models) and Sparrow.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning can degrade a model's robustness to distribution shifts.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] One mitigation is to linearly interpolate a fine-tuned model's weights with the weights of the original model, which can greatly increase out-of-distribution performance while largely retaining the in-distribution performance of the fine-tuned model.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Low-rank adaptation (LoRA) is an adapter-based technique for efficiently fine-tuning models.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] The basic idea is to design a low-rank matrix that is then added to the original matrix.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] An adapter, in this context, is a collection of low-rank matrices which, when added to a base model, produces a fine-tuned model.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] It allows for performance that approaches full-model fine-tuning with lower space requirements.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] A language model with billions of parameters may be LoRA fine-tuned with only several millions of parameters.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] LoRA-based fine-tuning has become popular in the Stable Diffusion community.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Support for LoRA was integrated into the diffusers library from Hugging Face.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Support for LoRA and similar techniques is also available for a wide range of other models through Hugging Face's *parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT)* package.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Representation fine-tuning (ReFT) is a technique developed by researchers at Stanford University aimed at fine-tuning large language models (LLMs) by modifying less than 1% of their representations.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Unlike parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT) methods, which mainly focus on updating weights, ReFT targets representations.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] ReFT methods operate on a frozen base model and learn task-specific interventions on hidden representations and train interventions that manipulate a small fraction of model representations to steer model behaviors towards solving downstream tasks at inference time.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] One specific method within the ReFT family is low-rank linear subspace ReFT (LoReFT), which intervenes on hidden representations in the linear subspace spanned by a low-rank projection matrix.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] LoReFT can be seen as the representation-based equivalent of low-rank adaptation (LoRA).
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning is common in natural language processing (NLP), especially in the domain of language modeling.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Large language models like OpenAI's series of GPT foundation models can be fine-tuned on data for specific downstream NLP tasks (tasks that use a pre-trained model) to improve performance over the unmodified pre-trained model.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Platforms such as Semrush's *AI Visibility Toolkit* and *Enterprise AIO* exemplify how fine-tuned models are being used for entity-level monitoring; tracking how named entities are referenced and represented within responses generated by large-language-model-based answer engines.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Commercially-offered large language models can sometimes be fine-tuned if the provider offers a fine-tuning API.
[src:transfer-learning/fine-tuning-deep-learning] As of June 19, 2023, language model fine-tuning APIs are offered by OpenAI and Microsoft Azure's Azure OpenAI Service for a subset of their models, as well as by Google Cloud Platform for some of their PaLM models, and by others.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Generative AI applications like large language models (LLM) are common examples of foundation models.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Building foundation models is often highly resource-intensive, with the most advanced models costing hundreds of millions of dollars to cover the expenses of acquiring, curating, and processing massive datasets, as well as the compute power required for training.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] These costs stem from the need for sophisticated infrastructure, extended training times, and advanced hardware, such as GPUs.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In contrast, adapting an existing foundation model for a specific task or using it directly is far less costly, as it uses pre-trained capabilities and typically requires only fine-tuning on smaller, task-specific datasets.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Early examples of foundation models are language models like OpenAI's GPT series and Google's BERT.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Beyond text, foundation models have been developed across a range of modalities—including DALL-E, Stable diffusion, and Flamingo for images, MusicGen and LLark for music, and RT-2 for robotic control.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models are also being developed for fields like astronomy, radiology, ophthalmology, genomics, coding, time series forecasting, mathematics, and chemistry.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] The term vision-language model (VLM) is also used as a near-synonym.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] As governments regulate foundation models, new legal definitions have emerged.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] The United States's definitions are the only ones to make reference to the size of a foundation model, and differ on magnitude.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Beyer and Eshoo's definition also specifies that foundation models must achieve a level of performance as to be a potential danger.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In contrast, the E.U. definition requires the model to be designed for generality of output.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] All definitions agree that foundation models must be trained on a broad range of data with potential applications in many domains.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Technologically, foundation models are built using established machine learning techniques like deep neural networks, transfer learning, and self-supervised learning.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models differ from previous techniques as they are general purpose models that function as a reusable infrastructure, instead of bespoke and one-off task-specific models.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Advances in computer parallelism (e.g., CUDA GPUs) and new developments in neural network architecture (e.g., Transformers), and the increased use of training data with minimal supervision all contributed to the rise of foundation models.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models began to materialize as the latest wave of deep learning models in the late 2010s.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Relative to most prior work on deep learning, these language models demonstrated the potential of training on much larger web-sourced datasets using self-supervised objectives (e.g. predicting the next word in a large corpus of text).
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] These approaches, which draw upon earlier works like word2vec and GloVe, deviated from prior supervised approaches that required annotated data (e.g. crowd-sourced labels).
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] The 2022 releases of Stable Diffusion and ChatGPT (initially powered by the GPT-3.5 model) led to foundation models and generative AI entering widespread public discourse.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Further, releases of LLaMA, Llama 2, and Mistral in 2023 contributed to a greater emphasis placed on how foundation models are released with open foundation models garnering a lot of support and scrutiny.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] As foundation models continue to improve, some AI researchers speculate that almost all next-generation foundation models will be considered frontier models.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Since the concept of dangerous capabilities is inherently subjective, there is no strict designation for what foundation models qualify as frontier models.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] The U.S. definition (via the AI Safety Institute at NIST) tied "frontier" status also to the compute technical threshold to create objective legal requirements.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Due to frontier models' unique capabilities, it is difficult to effectively regulate their development and deployment.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Because of their emergent nature, new dangerous capabilities can appear on their own in frontier models, both in the development stage and after being deployed.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Additionally, since frontier models continue to adapt after deployment, it remains difficult to mitigate all harms that arise from already-deployed models.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] If a frontier model happens to be open-source or is released online, the model can also disseminate rapidly, further hampering regulators by creating a lack of accountability.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In response, groups such as the Frontier Model Forum, founded by OpenAI, Anthropic, Google and Microsoft, were created to create safety standards for these advanced foundational models.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] A global network of governmental and intergovernmental bodies has emerged to create formal safety standards, including the Global Network of AI Safety Institutes (AISIs) and the G7"Hiroshima AI Process" (HAIP).
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Due to their adaptability to a wide range of use-cases, foundation models are sometimes considered to be examples of general-purpose AI.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In designing the EU AI Act, the European Parliament has stated that a new wave of general-purpose AI technologies shapes the overall AI ecosystem.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] The fuller structure of the ecosystem, in addition to the properties of specific general-purpose AI systems, influences the design of AI policy and research.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] General-purpose AI systems also often appear in people's everyday lives through applications and tools like ChatGPT or DALL-E.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Government agencies like EU Parliament have identified regulation of general-purpose AI, such as foundation models, to be a high priority.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] General-purpose AI systems are often characterized by large size, opacity, and potential for emergence, all of which can create unintended harms.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Such systems also heavily influence downstream applications, which further exacerbates the need for regulation.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In regards to prominent legislation, a number of stakeholders have pushed for the EU AI Act to include restrictions on general-purpose AI systems, all of which would also apply to foundation models.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] World models are sometimes described as foundation models.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] World models are a representation of an environment intended to predict the state of that environment after taking a set of actions, as well as to implicitly model physical concepts such as gravity.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Input prompts for world models can include text or images, as well as videos or 3D scenes, and the resulting 3D environments can be exported.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] World models, alongside embodied AI, multi-agent models, and neuroscience models of the brain, are seen as alternatives to large language models for achieving general artificial intelligence.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] World models do not have a fully agreed definition, but have been divided into two scopes: one for representing and understanding the current environment, and another for predicting the future state of that environment.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In the former view, world models are developed using model-based reinforcement learning and a Markov decision process, using model predictive control or Monte Carlo tree search to create policies.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] With the latter, (multimodal) large language models or video generation models can be used.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In addition, these environments can be immersive simulations for training AI agents that can interact in the real world.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] They suggested that agents trained on world models in environments that simulate reality could be applied to real world settings.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In 2022, Yann LeCun saw a world model (defined by him as a neural network that acts as a mental model for aspects of the world that are seen as relevant) as part of a larger system of cognitive architecture – other neural networks that are analogous to different regions of the brain.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In his view, this framework could lead to commonsense reasoning.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] LeCun has estimated that world models would be fully functional by the late 2020s to mid 2030s.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] World models are trained on a variety of data modalities, including text, images, audio and video, and have been applied to video generation.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] One open source dataset for world models includes 1 billion data points across multiple modalities (text, images, audio, video and point clouds), including 1 million manual annotations.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Google DeepMind has also released two world models in two-dimensional space and three-dimensional space, respectively, that were trained on video data, with Google claiming that the latter can be a training environment for AI agents.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Meta released a world model in June 2025, Tencent released an open source world model in July 2025.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Niantic, Inc. spinoff, Niantic Spatial, is developing a world model using anonymized player scans from Pokémon GO.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Other companies that are planning as of 2025 to build world models include ByteDance and xAI.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Fei-Fei Li views world models as applying to robotics and creative works.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Due to the complexity of these models, she advocates for more complex strategies in data acquisition, data engineering, data processing, and synthesizing data.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] She co-founded a startup on building world models, which, as of 2024, planned to do so in three phases: incorporating an understanding of three-dimensional space along with time; support for augmented reality; and support for robotics.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Her startup, World Labs, released its commercial world model, Marble, in November 2025.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] World models are intended for use in interactive media (such as video games and movies) and environment simulation.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Proposed use cases for world models include action planning and outcome prediction.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Other applications include social simulacra to simulate social systems.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] *Wired* compared world models to the metaverse, while *Business Insider* noted possible military applications.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In 2025, world models are being applied to drone warfare, robotics, and self-driving vehicles.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] *The Wall Street Journal* speculated that world models could improve spatial reasoning of artificial intelligence models and successfully automate both blue-collar and white-collar jobs.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] As of October 2025, research has shown mixed results in the spatial reasoning capabilities of text-to-video models (in particular, Veo 3).
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Creative professionals have expressed concern that world models could disrupt jobs in their industries.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Other concerns include data privacy, simulation of harmful situations, misinformation and disinformation, emergent behaviors, and copyright.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] For a foundation model to effectively generalize, it must acquire rich representations of the training data.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] As a result, expressive model architectures that efficiently process large-scale data are often preferred in building foundation models.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Currently, the Transformer architecture is the de facto choice for building foundation models across a range of modalities.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models are built by optimizing a loss function, which is a mathematical function that determines how model parameters are updated based on model predictions on training data.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Language models are often trained with a next-tokens prediction objective, which refers to the extent at which the model is able to predict the next token in a sequence.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Image models are commonly trained with contrastive learning or diffusion training objectives.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] For contrastive learning, images are randomly augmented before being evaluated on the resulting similarity of the model's representations.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] For diffusion models, images are noised and the model learns to gradually de-noise via the objective.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Multimodal training objectives also exist, with some separating images and text during training, while others examine them concurrently.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In general, the training objectives for foundation models promote the learning of broadly useful representations of data.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] With the rise of foundation models and the larger datasets that power them, a training objective must be able to parse through internet-scale data for meaningful data points.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Additionally, since foundation models are designed to solve a general range of tasks, training objectives ought to be *domain complete*, or able to solve a broad set of downstream capabilities within the given domain.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Lastly, foundation model training objectives should seek to scale well and be computationally efficient.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] With model size and compute power both being relevant constraints, a training objective must be able to overcome such bottlenecks.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models are trained on a large quantity of data, working under the maxim "the more data, the better." Performance evaluation does show that more data generally leads to better performance, but other issues arise as data quantity grows.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Tasks like managing the dataset, integrating data across new applications, ensuring adherence to data licenses, and maintaining data quality all become more difficult as data size grows.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] The specific demands of foundation models have only exacerbated such issues, as it remains the norm for large foundation models to use public web-scraped data.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models include also search engines data and SEO meta tags data.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Public web data remains a plentiful resource, but it also demands stringent moderation and data processing from foundation model developers before it can be successfully integrated into the training pipeline.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Training foundation models often runs the risk of violating user privacy, as private data can be disclosed, collected, or used in ways beyond the stated scope.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Even if no private data is leaked, models can still inadvertently compromise security through learned behavior in the resulting foundation model.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Data quality is another key point, as web-scraped data frequently contains biased, duplicate, and toxic material.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Once foundation models are deployed, ensuring high-quality data is still an issue, as undesirable behavior can still emerge from small subsets of data.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] The size of foundation models also brings about issues with the computer systems they run on.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] The average foundation model is too large to be run within a single accelerator's memory and the initial training process requires an expensive amount of resources.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Such issues are predicted to further exacerbate in future as foundation models grow to new heights.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Due to this constraint, researchers have begun looking into compressing model size through tight model inference.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] GPUs are the most common choice of compute hardware for machine learning, due to high memory storage and strong power.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Typical foundation model training requires many GPUs in a distributed computing setup, connected in parallel with fast interconnects.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Acquiring a sufficient amount of GPUs of requisite compute efficiency is a challenge for many foundation model developers, one that has led to an increasing dilemma in the field.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Larger models require greater compute power, but often at the cost of improved compute efficiency.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Since training remains time-consuming and expensive, the tradeoff between compute power and compute efficiency has led only a few select companies to afford the production costs for large, state of the art foundation models.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Some techniques like compression and distillation can make inference more affordable, but they fail to completely shore up this weakness.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] The accuracy and capabilities of foundation models often scale predictably with the size of the model and the amount of the training data.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Specifically, scaling laws have been discovered, which are data-based empirical trends that relate resources (data, model size, compute usage) to model capabilities.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Particularly, a model's scale is defined by compute, dataset size, and the number of parameters, all of which exhibit a power-law relationship with end performance.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] However, broken scaling laws have been discovered in which this relationship smoothly transitions (at points referred to as break(s)) from a power law with one exponent to a power law with another (different) exponent.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] When one does not collect any points near (or after) the break(s), it can be difficult to obtain an accurate extrapolation.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models are inherently multi-purpose: to use these model for a specific use case requires some form of adaptation.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] At a minimum, models need to be adapted to perform the task of interest (task specification), but often better performance can be achieved by more extensive adaptation to the domain of interest (domain specialization).
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] A variety of methods (e.g. prompting, in-context learning, fine-tuning, LoRA) provide different tradeoffs between the costs of adaptation and the extent to which models are specialized.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Some major facets to consider when adapting a foundation model are compute budget and data availability.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models can be very large, up to trillions of parameters in size, so adapting the entirety of a foundation model can be computationally expensive.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Therefore, developers sometimes adapt only the last neural layer or only the bias vectors to save time and space.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] For particularly niche applications, specific data may also not be available to adapt the foundation model sufficiently.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In such circumstances, data must be manually labeled, which is costly and can demand expert knowledge.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Evaluation is a key part of developing foundation models.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Not only does evaluation allow for tracking progress of high-performance models, it also creates benchmarks for future model development.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Stakeholders rely on evaluations to understand model behaviors and gain insight into their various attributes.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Traditionally, foundation models are evaluated relative to each other through standardized task benchmarks like MMLU, MMMU, HumanEval, and GSM8K.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Given that foundation models are multi-purpose, increasingly meta-benchmarks are developed that aggregate different underlying benchmarks.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Examples include LM-Harness, BIG-Bench, HELM, OpenLLM Leaderboard, DecodingTrust, and HEIM.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Since foundation models' utility depends on their own general capabilities and the performance of fine-tuned applications, evaluation must cover both metrics.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Proper evaluation examines both a foundation model's downstream applications in aggregate and the direct properties the foundation model holds.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] To ensure further equity in evaluation, certain existing evaluation frameworks account for all adaptation resources, which leads to more informed analyses for the benefit of all stakeholders.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models' general capabilities allow them to fulfill a unique role in the AI ecosystem, fueled by many upstream and downstream technologies.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Training a foundation model requires several resources (e.g. data, compute, labor, hardware, code), with foundation models often involving immense amounts of data and compute (also referred to as computational power).
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Due to foundation models' large development costs and inexpensive adaptation requirements, the AI landscape has shifted to a small subset of AI companies making foundation models for downstream adaptation.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Thus, most foundation model companies outsource this step to specialized data providers (e.g.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Scale AI, Surge) and compute providers (e.g.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Amazon Bedrock, Google Cloud, Microsoft Azure).
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] The foundation model developer itself will then take the data and use the supplied compute to actually train the foundation model.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] After the foundation model is completely built, much of the data and labor requirements abate.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In this development process, hardware and compute are the most necessary, and also the most exclusive resources.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] To train larger and more complex AI, a sufficient amount of compute is key.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] However, compute is consolidated in the hands of a few, select entities, which most foundation model developers depend on.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] As such, the foundation model pipeline is concentrated heavily around these providers.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Compute is also costly; in 2023, AI companies spent more than 80% of total capital on compute resources.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models require a large amount of general data to power their capabilities.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Early foundation models scraped from subsets of the internet to provide this data information.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] As the size and scope of foundation models grows, larger quantities of internet scraping becomes necessary, resulting in higher likelihoods of biased or toxic data.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] This toxic or biased data can disproportionately harm marginalized groups and exacerbate existing prejudices.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] To address this issue of low-quality data that arose with unsupervised training, some foundation model developers have turned to manual filtering.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] This practice, known as data labor, comes with its own host of issues.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Such manual data detoxification is often outsourced to reduce labor costs, with some workers making less than $2 per hour.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] The foundation model will then be hosted online either via the developer or via an external organization.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Once released, other parties can create applications based on the foundation model, whether through fine-tuning or wholly new purposes.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] People can then access these applications to serve their various means, allowing one foundation model to power and reach a wide audience.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] After a foundation model is built, it can be released in one of many ways.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] There are many facets to a release: the asset itself, who has access, how access changes over time, and the conditions on use.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] All these factors contribute to how a foundation model will affect downstream applications.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] In particular, the two most common forms of foundation model release are through APIs and direct model downloads.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] When a model is released via an API, users can query the model and receive responses, but cannot directly access the model itself.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Comparatively, the model could be directly downloadable for users to access and modify.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Both release strategies are often classified as an open release.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] The exact definition of an open release is disputed, but widely accepted requirements are provided by the Open Source Initiative.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Some open foundation models are: PaLM 2, Llama 2, Granite, and Mistral.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] While open foundation models can further research and development more easily, they are also more susceptible to misuse.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Open foundation models can be downloaded by anyone, and particularly powerful models can be fine-tuned to intentionally or unintentionally cause harm.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] During a closed release, the foundation model cannot be accessed by the public, but is used internally by an organization.
[src:transfer-learning/foundation-model] Such releases are considered safer, but offer no additional value to the research community or the public at large.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] In machine learning (ML), **feature learning** or **representation learning** is a set of techniques that allow a system to automatically discover the representations needed for feature detection or classification from raw data.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] This replaces manual feature engineering and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that ML tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] However, real-world data, such as image, video, and sensor data, have not yielded to attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Supervised feature learning is learning features from labeled data.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The data label allows the system to compute an error term, the degree to which the system fails to produce the label, which can then be used as feedback to correct the learning process (reduce/minimize the error).
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Dictionary learning develops a set (dictionary) of representative elements from the input data such that each data point can be represented as a weighted sum of the representative elements.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The dictionary elements and the weights may be found by minimizing the average representation error (over the input data), together with *L1* regularization on the weights to enable sparsity (i.e., the representation of each data point has only a few nonzero weights).
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Supervised dictionary learning exploits both the structure underlying the input data and the labels for optimizing the dictionary elements.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] For example, this supervised dictionary learning technique applies dictionary learning on classification problems by jointly optimizing the dictionary elements, weights for representing data points, and parameters of the classifier based on the input data.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Neural networks are a family of learning algorithms that use a "network" consisting of multiple layers of inter-connected nodes.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] It is inspired by the animal nervous system, where the nodes are viewed as neurons and edges are viewed as synapses.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Each edge has an associated weight, and the network defines computational rules for passing input data from the network's input layer to the output layer.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] A network function associated with a neural network characterizes the relationship between input and output layers, which is parameterized by the weights.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] With appropriately defined network functions, various learning tasks can be performed by minimizing a cost function over the network function (weights).
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Multilayer neural networks can be used to perform feature learning, since they learn a representation of their input at the hidden layer(s) which is subsequently used for classification or regression at the output layer.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The most popular network architecture of this type is Siamese networks.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Unsupervised feature learning is learning features from unlabeled data.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The goal of unsupervised feature learning is often to discover low-dimensional features that capture some structure underlying the high-dimensional input data.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] When the feature learning is performed in an unsupervised way, it enables a form of semisupervised learning where features learned from an unlabeled dataset are then employed to improve performance in a supervised setting with labeled data.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Several approaches are introduced in the following.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] K-means clustering can be used to group an unlabeled set of inputs into *k* clusters, and then use the centroids of these clusters to produce features.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] These features can be produced in several ways.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The simplest is to add *k* binary features to each sample, where each feature *j* has value one iff the *j*th centroid learned by *k*-means is the closest to the sample under consideration.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] It is also possible to use the distances to the clusters as features, perhaps after transforming them through a radial basis function (a technique that has been used to train RBF networks).
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Coates and Ng note that certain variants of *k*-means behave similarly to sparse coding algorithms.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] In a comparative evaluation of unsupervised feature learning methods, Coates, Lee and Ng found that *k*-means clustering with an appropriate transformation outperforms the more recently invented auto-encoders and RBMs on an image classification task.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] *K*-means also improves performance in the domain of NLP, specifically for named-entity recognition; there, it competes with Brown clustering, as well as with distributed word representations (also known as neural word embeddings).
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Principal component analysis (PCA) is often used for dimension reduction.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Equivalently, these singular vectors are the eigenvectors corresponding to the *p* largest eigenvalues of the sample covariance matrix of the input vectors.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] These *p* singular vectors are the feature vectors learned from the input data, and they represent directions along which the data has the largest variations.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] PCA is a linear feature learning approach since the *p* singular vectors are linear functions of the data matrix.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The singular vectors can be generated via a simple algorithm with *p* iterations.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] In the *i*th iteration, the projection of the data matrix on the *(i-1)*th eigenvector is subtracted, and the *i*th singular vector is found as the right singular vector corresponding to the largest singular of the residual data matrix.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] First, it assumes that the directions with large variance are of most interest, which may not be the case.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] PCA only relies on orthogonal transformations of the original data, and it exploits only the first- and second-order moments of the data, which may not well characterize the data distribution.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Furthermore, PCA can effectively reduce dimension only when the input data vectors are correlated (which results in a few dominant eigenvalues).
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Local linear embedding (LLE) is a nonlinear learning approach for generating low-dimensional neighbor-preserving representations from (unlabeled) high-dimension input.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The approach was proposed by Roweis and Saul (2000).
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The general idea of LLE is to reconstruct the original high-dimensional data using lower-dimensional points while maintaining some geometric properties of the neighborhoods in the original data set.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The second step is for "dimension reduction," by looking for vectors in a lower-dimensional space that minimizes the representation error using the optimized weights in the first step.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Note that in the first step, the weights are optimized with fixed data, which can be solved as a least squares problem.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] In the second step, lower-dimensional points are optimized with fixed weights, which can be solved via sparse eigenvalue decomposition.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The reconstruction weights obtained in the first step capture the "intrinsic geometric properties" of a neighborhood in the input data.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] It is assumed that original data lie on a smooth lower-dimensional manifold, and the "intrinsic geometric properties" captured by the weights of the original data are also expected to be on the manifold.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] This is why the same weights are used in the second step of LLE.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Compared with PCA, LLE is more powerful in exploiting the underlying data structure.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Independent component analysis (ICA) is a technique for forming a data representation using a weighted sum of independent non-Gaussian components.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The assumption of non-Gaussian is imposed since the weights cannot be uniquely determined when all the components follow Gaussian distribution.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Unsupervised dictionary learning does not utilize data labels and exploits the structure underlying the data for optimizing dictionary elements.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] An example of unsupervised dictionary learning is sparse coding, which aims to learn basis functions (dictionary elements) for data representation from unlabeled input data.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Sparse coding can be applied to learn overcomplete dictionaries, where the number of dictionary elements is larger than the dimension of the input data.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Aharon et al. proposed algorithm K-SVD for learning a dictionary of elements that enables sparse representation.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The hierarchical architecture of the biological neural system inspires deep learning architectures for feature learning by stacking multiple layers of learning nodes.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] These architectures are often designed based on the assumption of distributed representation: observed data is generated by the interactions of many different factors on multiple levels.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] In a deep learning architecture, the output of each intermediate layer can be viewed as a representation of the original input data.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Each level uses the representation produced by the previous, lower level as input, and produces new representations as output, which are then fed to higher levels.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The input at the bottom layer is raw data, and the output of the final, highest layer is the final low-dimensional feature or representation.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Restricted Boltzmann machines (RBMs) are often used as a building block for multilayer learning architectures.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] An RBM can be represented by an undirected bipartite graph consisting of a group of binary hidden variables, a group of visible variables, and edges connecting the hidden and visible nodes.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] It is a special case of the more general Boltzmann machines with the constraint of no intra-node connections.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Each edge in an RBM is associated with a weight.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The weights together with the connections define an energy function, based on which a joint distribution of visible and hidden nodes can be devised.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Based on the topology of the RBM, the hidden (visible) variables are independent, conditioned on the visible (hidden) variables.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Such conditional independence facilitates computations.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] An RBM can be viewed as a single layer architecture for unsupervised feature learning.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] In particular, the visible variables correspond to input data, and the hidden variables correspond to feature detectors.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The weights can be trained by maximizing the probability of visible variables using Hinton's contrastive divergence (CD) algorithm.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] In general, training RBMs by solving the maximization problem tends to result in non-sparse representations.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Sparse RBM was proposed to enable sparse representations.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The idea is to add a regularization term in the objective function of data likelihood, which penalizes the deviation of the expected hidden variables from a small constant p .
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] RBMs have also been used to obtain *disentangled* representations of data, where interesting features map to separate hidden units.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] An autoencoder consisting of an encoder and a decoder is a paradigm for deep learning architectures.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] An example is provided by Hinton and Salakhutdinov where the encoder uses raw data (e.g., image) as input and produces feature or representation as output and the decoder uses the extracted feature from the encoder as input and reconstructs the original input raw data as output.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The encoder and decoder are constructed by stacking multiple layers of RBMs.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The parameters involved in the architecture were originally trained in a greedy layer-by-layer manner: after one layer of feature detectors is learned, they are fed up as visible variables for training the corresponding RBM.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Current approaches typically apply end-to-end training with stochastic gradient descent methods.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Training can be repeated until some stopping criteria are satisfied.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Self-supervised representation learning is learning features by training on the structure of unlabeled data rather than relying on explicit labels for an information signal.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] This approach has enabled the combined use of deep neural network architectures and larger unlabeled datasets to produce deep feature representations.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Training tasks typically fall under the classes of either contrastive, generative or both.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Contrastive representation learning trains representations for associated data pairs, called positive samples, to be aligned, while pairs with no relation, called negative samples, are contrasted.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] A larger portion of negative samples is typically necessary in order to prevent catastrophic collapse, which is when all inputs are mapped to the same representation.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Generative representation learning tasks the model with producing the correct data to either match a restricted input or reconstruct the full input from a lower dimensional representation.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] A common setup for self-supervised representation learning of a certain data type (e.g. text, image, audio, video) is to pretrain the model using large datasets of general context, unlabeled data.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Depending on the context, the result of this is either a set of representations for common data segments (e.g. words) which new data can be broken into, or a neural network able to convert each new data point (e.g. image) into a set of lower dimensional features.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] In either case, the output representations can then be used as an initialization in many different problem settings where labeled data may be limited.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Specialization of the model to specific tasks is typically done with supervised learning, either by fine-tuning the model / representations with the labels as the signal, or freezing the representations and training an additional model which takes them as an input.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Many self-supervised training schemes have been developed for use in representation learning of various modalities, often first showing successful application in text or image before being transferred to other data types.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Word2vec is a word embedding technique which learns to represent words through self-supervision over each word and its neighboring words in a sliding window across a large corpus of text.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The model has two possible training schemes to produce word vector representations, one generative and one contrastive.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The first is word prediction given each of the neighboring words as an input.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The second is training on the representation similarity for neighboring words and representation dissimilarity for random pairs of words.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] A limitation of word2vec is that only the pairwise co-occurrence structure of the data is used, and not the ordering or entire set of context words.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] More recent transformer-based representation learning approaches attempt to solve this with word prediction tasks.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] GPTs pretrain on next word prediction using prior input words as context, whereas BERT masks random tokens in order to provide bidirectional context.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Other self-supervised techniques extend word embeddings by finding representations for larger text structures such as sentences or paragraphs in the input data.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Doc2vec extends the generative training approach in word2vec by adding an additional input to the word prediction task based on the paragraph it is within, and is therefore intended to represent paragraph level context.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The domain of image representation learning has employed many different self-supervised training techniques, including transformation, inpainting, patch discrimination and clustering.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Many other self-supervised methods use siamese networks, which generate different views of the image through various augmentations that are then aligned to have similar representations.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] The challenge is avoiding collapsing solutions where the model encodes all images to the same representation.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] SimCLR is a contrastive approach which uses negative examples in order to generate image representations with a ResNet CNN.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Bootstrap Your Own Latent (BYOL) removes the need for negative samples by encoding one of the views with a slow moving average of the model parameters as they are being modified during training.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Another approach is to maximize mutual information, a measure of similarity, between the representations of associated structures within the graph.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] An example is Deep Graph Infomax, which uses contrastive self-supervision based on mutual information between the representation of a "patch" around each node, and a summary representation of the entire graph.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Negative samples are obtained by pairing the graph representation with either representations from another graph in a multigraph training setting, or corrupted patch representations in single graph training.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] With analogous results in masked prediction and clustering, video representation learning approaches are often similar to image techniques but must utilize the temporal sequence of video frames as an additional learned structure.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Examples include VCP, which masks video clips and trains to choose the correct one given a set of clip options, and Xu et al., who train a 3D-CNN to identify the original order given a shuffled set of video clips.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Self-supervised representation techniques have also been applied to many audio data formats, particularly for speech processing.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Wav2vec 2.0 discretizes the audio waveform into timesteps via temporal convolutions, and then trains a transformer on masked prediction of random timesteps using a contrastive loss.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] This is similar to the BERT language model, except as in many SSL approaches to video, the model chooses among a set of options rather than over the entire word vocabulary.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Self-supervised learning has also been used to develop joint representations of multiple data types.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Approaches usually rely on some natural or human-derived association between the modalities as an implicit label, for instance video clips of animals or objects with characteristic sounds, or captions written to describe images.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] CLIP produces a joint image-text representation space by training to align image and text encodings from a large dataset of image-caption pairs using a contrastive loss.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Multimodal representation models are typically unable to assume direct correspondence of representations in the different modalities, since the precise alignment can often be noisy or ambiguous.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] For example, the text "dog" could be paired with many different pictures of dogs, and correspondingly a picture of a dog could be captioned with varying degrees of specificity.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] This limitation means that downstream tasks may require an additional generative mapping network between modalities to achieve optimal performance, such as in DALLE-2 for text to image generation.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Dynamic representation learning methods generate latent embeddings for dynamic systems such as dynamic networks.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Since particular distance functions are invariant under particular linear transformations, different sets of embedding vectors can actually represent the same/similar information.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Therefore, for a dynamic system, a temporal difference in its embeddings may be explained by misalignment of embeddings due to arbitrary transformations and/or actual changes in the system.
[src:transfer-learning/representation-learning] Therefore, generally speaking, temporal embeddings learned via dynamic representation learning methods should be inspected for any spurious changes and be aligned before consequent dynamic analyses.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] In machine learning, **supervised learning** (**SL**) is a type of machine learning paradigm where an algorithm learns to map input data to a specific output based on example input-output pairs.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] This process involves training a statistical model using labeled data, meaning each piece of input data is provided with the correct output.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The term "supervised" refers to the role of a teacher or supervisor who provides this training data, guiding the algorithm towards correct predictions.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] For instance, if you want a model to identify cats in images, supervised learning would involve feeding it many images of cats (inputs) that are explicitly labeled "cat" (outputs).
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The goal of supervised learning is for the trained model to accurately predict the output for new, unseen data.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] This requires the algorithm to effectively generalize from the training examples, a quality measured by its *generalization error*.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Supervised learning is commonly used for tasks like classification (predicting a category, e.g., spam or not spam) and regression (predicting a continuous value, e.g., house prices).
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The training set needs to be representative of the real-world use of the function.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Thus, a set of input objects is gathered together with corresponding outputs, either from human experts or from measurements.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Determine the input feature representation of the learned function.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The accuracy of the learned function depends strongly on how the input object is represented.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Typically, the input object is transformed into a feature vector, which contains a number of features that are descriptive of the object.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The number of features should not be too large, because of the curse of dimensionality; but should contain enough information to accurately predict the output.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Determine the structure of the learned function and corresponding learning algorithm.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] For example, one may choose to use support-vector machines or decision trees.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Run the learning algorithm on the gathered training set.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Some supervised learning algorithms require the user to determine certain control parameters.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] These parameters may be adjusted by optimizing performance on a subset (called a *validation set*) of the training set, or via cross-validation.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Evaluate the accuracy of the learned function.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] After parameter adjustment and learning, the performance of the resulting function should be measured on a test set that is separate from the training set.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] A wide range of supervised learning algorithms are available, each with its strengths and weaknesses.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] There is no single learning algorithm that works best on all supervised learning problems (see the No free lunch theorem).
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] A first issue is the tradeoff between *bias* and *variance*.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Imagine that we have available several different, but equally good, training data sets.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] A learning algorithm is biased for a particular input x if, when trained on each of these data sets, it is systematically incorrect when predicting the correct output for x .
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] A learning algorithm has high variance for a particular input x if it predicts different output values when trained on different training sets.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The prediction error of a learned classifier is related to the sum of the bias and the variance of the learning algorithm.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Generally, there is a tradeoff between bias and variance.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] A learning algorithm with low bias must be "flexible" so that it can fit the data well.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] But if the learning algorithm is too flexible, it will fit each training data set differently, and hence have high variance.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] A key aspect of many supervised learning methods is that they are able to adjust this tradeoff between bias and variance (either automatically or by providing a bias/variance parameter that the user can adjust).
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The second issue is of the amount of training data available relative to the complexity of the "true" function (classifier or regression function).
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] If the true function is simple, then an "inflexible" learning algorithm with high bias and low variance will be able to learn it from a small amount of data.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] A third issue is the dimensionality of the input space.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] If the input feature vectors have large dimensions, learning the function can be difficult even if the true function only depends on a small number of those features.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] This is because the many "extra" dimensions can confuse the learning algorithm and cause it to have high variance.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Hence, input data of large dimensions typically requires tuning the classifier to have low variance and high bias.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] In practice, if the engineer can manually remove irrelevant features from the input data, it will likely improve the accuracy of the learned function.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] In addition, there are many algorithms for feature selection that seek to identify the relevant features and discard the irrelevant ones.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] This is an instance of the more general strategy of dimensionality reduction, which seeks to map the input data into a lower-dimensional space prior to running the supervised learning algorithm.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] A fourth issue is the degree of noise in the desired output values (the supervisory target variables).
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] If the desired output values are often incorrect (because of human error or sensor errors), then the learning algorithm should not attempt to find a function that exactly matches the training examples.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Attempting to fit the data too carefully leads to overfitting.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] You can overfit even when there are no measurement errors (stochastic noise) if the function you are trying to learn is too complex for your learning model.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] In such a situation, the part of the target function that cannot be modeled "corrupts" your training data – this phenomenon has been called deterministic noise.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] When either type of noise is present, it is better to go with a higher bias, lower variance estimator.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] In practice, there are several approaches to alleviate noise in the output values such as early stopping to prevent overfitting as well as detecting and removing the noisy training examples prior to training the supervised learning algorithm.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] There are several algorithms that identify noisy training examples and removing the suspected noisy training examples prior to training has decreased generalization error with statistical significance.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] When considering a new application, the engineer can compare multiple learning algorithms and experimentally determine which one works best on the problem at hand (see cross-validation).
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Tuning the performance of a learning algorithm can be very time-consuming.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Given fixed resources, it is often better to spend more time collecting additional training data and more informative features than it is to spend extra time tuning the learning algorithms.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Given a set of N training examples of the form $\{(x_{1},y_{1}),...,(x_{N},\;y_{N})\}$ such that $x_{i}$ is the feature vector of the i -th example and $y_{i}$ is its label (i.e., class), a learning algorithm seeks a function $g:X\to Y$ , where X is the input space and Y is the output space.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The function g is an element of some space of possible functions G , usually called the *hypothesis space*.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] It is sometimes convenient to represent g using a scoring function $f:X\times Y\to \mathbb {R}$ such that g is defined as returning the y value that gives the highest score: $g(x)={\underset {y}{\arg \max }}\;f(x,y)$ .
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Let F denote the space of scoring functions.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Although G and F can be any space of functions, many learning algorithms are probabilistic models where g takes the form of a conditional probability model $g(x)={\underset {y}{\arg \max }}\;P(y|x)$ , or f takes the form of a joint probability model $f(x,y)=P(x,y)$ .
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] For example, naive Bayes and linear discriminant analysis are joint probability models, whereas logistic regression is a conditional probability model.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] There are two basic approaches to choosing f or g : empirical risk minimization and structural risk minimization.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Empirical risk minimization seeks the function that best fits the training data.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Structural risk minimization includes a *penalty function* that controls the bias/variance tradeoff.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] In both cases, it is assumed that the training set consists of a sample of independent and identically distributed pairs, $(x_{i},\;y_{i})$ .
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] In order to measure how well a function fits the training data, a loss function $L:Y\times Y\to \mathbb {R} ^{\geq 0}$ is defined.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The *risk* $R(g)$ of function g is defined as the expected loss of g .
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] In empirical risk minimization, the supervised learning algorithm seeks the function g that minimizes $R(g)$ .
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Hence, a supervised learning algorithm can be constructed by applying an optimization algorithm to find g .
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] When g is a conditional probability distribution $P(y|x)$ and the loss function is the negative log likelihood: $L(y,{\hat {y}})=-\log P(y|x)$ , then empirical risk minimization is equivalent to maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] When G contains many candidate functions or the training set is not sufficiently large, empirical risk minimization leads to high variance and poor generalization.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The learning algorithm is able to memorize the training examples without generalizing well (overfitting).
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Structural risk minimization seeks to prevent overfitting by incorporating a regularization penalty into the optimization.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The regularization penalty can be viewed as implementing a form of Occam's razor that prefers simpler functions over more complex ones.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] A wide variety of penalties have been employed that correspond to different definitions of complexity.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] A popular regularization penalty is $\sum _{j}\beta _{j}^{2}$ , which is the squared Euclidean norm of the weights, also known as the $L_{2}$ norm.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Other norms include the $L_{1}$ norm, $\sum _{j}|\beta _{j}|$ , and the $L_{0}$ "norm", which is the number of non-zero $\beta _{j}$ s.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The parameter $\lambda$ controls the bias-variance tradeoff.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] When $\lambda =0$ , this gives empirical risk minimization with low bias and high variance.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] When $\lambda$ is large, the learning algorithm will have high bias and low variance.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The value of $\lambda$ can be chosen empirically via cross-validation.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The complexity penalty has a Bayesian interpretation as the negative log prior probability of g , $-\log P(g)$ , in which case $J(g)$ is the posterior probability of g .
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] The training methods described above are *discriminative training* methods, because they seek to find a function g that discriminates well between the different output values (see discriminative model).
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] Generative training algorithms are often simpler and more computationally efficient than discriminative training algorithms.
[src:transfer-learning/supervised-learning] In some cases, the solution can be computed in closed form as in naive Bayes and linear discriminant analysis.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] Since transfer learning makes use of training with multiple objective functions it is related to cost-sensitive machine learning and multi-objective optimization.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] In 1976, Bozinovski and Fulgosi published a paper addressing transfer learning in neural network training.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] The paper gives a mathematical and geometrical model of the topic.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] In 1981, a report considered the application of transfer learning to a dataset of images representing letters of computer terminals, experimentally demonstrating positive and negative transfer learning.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] In 1992, Lorien Pratt formulated the discriminability-based transfer (DBT) algorithm.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] By 1998, the field had advanced to include multi-task learning, along with more formal theoretical foundations.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] Influential publications on transfer learning include the book *Learning to Learn* in 1998, a 2009 survey and a 2019 survey.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] Ng said in his NIPS 2016 tutorial that TL would become the next driver of machine learning commercial success after supervised learning.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] In the 2020 paper, "Rethinking Pre-Training and self-training", Zoph et al. reported that pre-training can hurt accuracy, and advocate self-training instead.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] The definition of transfer learning is given in terms of domains and tasks.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] A domain ${\mathcal {D}}$ consists of: a feature space ${\mathcal {X}}$ and a marginal probability distribution $P(X)$ , where $X=\{x_{1},...,x_{n}\}\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] Given a specific domain, ${\mathcal {D}}=\{{\mathcal {X}},P(X)\}$ , a task consists of two components: a label space ${\mathcal {Y}}$ and an objective predictive function $f:{\mathcal {X}}\rightarrow {\mathcal {Y}}$ .
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] The function f is used to predict the corresponding label $f(x)$ of a new instance x .
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] Algorithms for transfer learning are available in Markov logic networks and Bayesian networks.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] Transfer learning has been applied to cancer subtype discovery, building utilization, general game playing, text classification, digit recognition, medical imaging and spam filtering.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] It was noted that this relationship worked in both directions, showing that EEG brainwaves can likewise be used to classify EMG signals.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] The experiments noted that the accuracy of neural networks and convolutional neural networks were improved through transfer learning both prior to any learning (compared to standard random weight distribution) and at the end of the learning process (asymptote).
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] That is, results are improved by exposure to another domain.
[src:transfer-learning/transfer-learning] Moreover, the end-user of a pre-trained model can change the structure of fully-connected layers to improve performance.
